	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Quivers are a &quot;live and learn&quot; experiance. At least this lesson costs you only a few coins. Most you pay for with your life exp.<BR>
The lesson: Any item container can be a quiver.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Tailor-made 10 slot backpacks make the best Quivers.<BR>
Merchant 8 slot backpacks make the most commonly used Quivers.<BR>
Looted 'large bags' (6 slots) is the lightest per arrow caried, and cheapest.<BR>
***SECRET*** (so shhhh ;)<BR>
Rangers Only (I think). For details, look up the Raincaller quest (Trueshot Longbow upgrade). One of the sub-quests is to get 10 items and put them in a (drum roll...)<BR>
10 slot small chest! It's light weight too! Just don't hit the combine button ;)<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Nother reason Arrow doesn't &quot;auto load&quot; is if you run out of that model arrow. Say if you have 40 merchant (40m) and 140 flether-made (140f). You have 20m in your ammo slot, and 20m in your backpack. You also have 140f in your backpack. After 40 shots, your ammo slot will 'run dry', until you put 1-20f arrows in it.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
What I want to know:<BR>
I have seen a &quot;fleeting quiver&quot; pattern for a tailor-made item. Anyone know if on has been made?<BR>
<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
